Environment-Climate: For a European New Deal
BRUSSELS – In Brussels as in other European capitals, the "Green New Deal" is on everyone's lips, echoing the visionary economic program launched by President Franklin D. Roosevelt in 1933.
But this time, it's about the environment and the climate.
And Europe is the continent where we can and must act.
The European Union's commitment to these issues is not new: we have had a common program since 1972.
Later in 2005, the EU established the first emissions trading system, which remains the world's first CO2 market.
And in 2015, the EU played a leading role in negotiating the Paris Agreement, committing to reduce its own greenhouse gas emissions by 40% (base: 1990 levels).
But these measures, although important, are not sufficient to address the challenges facing the world today.
The increasingly high temperatures could lead to the complete disappearance of Arctic sea ice by 2050.
Bees and many other insects are dying out, while microplastic pollution is ubiquitous in our environment.
And the number of victims of respiratory diseases increases as air pollution worsens.
We nevertheless have reasons to remain optimistic.
Let's look at these people, growing more numerous day by day, ready to act to question their lifestyles. Just like these students and entire families descending into the streets of Stockholm, Prague, Brussels, and Milan every Thursday!
Companies, too, commit themselves, recognizing the unparalleled economic potential of a green economy.
But it is often the politicians and political leaders, at the national as well as European level, who lack ambition.
We have a window of opportunity to act. Seize it!
And let us make a green Europe our top political priority for the years to come, focusing on three key areas.
First, Europe must become a carbon-neutral economy by 2050.
If we want to limit global warming to 1.5°C, we have no other choice: the EU's net carbon dioxide emissions must be reduced to zero by mid-century.
Together, we can invest massively in the future of our mobility, energy-efficient buildings, and renewable energies, as well as in key technologies such as hydrogen batteries, new generations of solar panels, and green chemistry.
Together, we must also impose strict CO2 emission limits on new private cars, public transport, as well as commercial maritime and air transport.
And, by working closely with our automotive industry, we can make Europe the leading continent for electric vehicles by 2030.
Secondly, Europe must play a leading role in the responsible use of resources and become a true circular economy that is waste-efficient.
Each year, 8 billion tons of materials are transformed into energy or products in the European Union.
But only 0.6 billion tonnes come from recycling.
We need to do much better, which will require focusing on four areas: food waste and the bioeconomy, textiles, construction, and rapidly evolving consumer goods.
Let's get to work right away, by launching, for example, an European initiative to combat planned obsolescence of household appliances and electronic devices, and by abolishing plastics from our value chains.
Thirdly, we must do much more to protect biodiversity.
According to the WWF, wild species populations have decreased by about 60% worldwide since 1970.
The United Nations Conference on Biodiversity, which will take place in Beijing next year, will be decisive.
Once again, the EU must show the way.
We must strengthen the EU's legislation on species protection and put forward an ambitious plan for the blue economy and the preservation of our seas.
We must also launch a genuine debate with our farmers (not against them!) on the revision of our standards and the modernization of the Common Agricultural Policy to support this green transition.
But these massive projects that await us, we will not be able to accomplish them if it is always the same – and the most vulnerable – who are asked to bear the costs.
All measures under consideration must therefore first and foremost be designed to minimize social costs.
And in parallel, we must today work with our partners for international cooperation, fighting against unfair competition.
For it is of no use to have strict European rules on pesticides or forest management if our imported food and timber are produced without respecting sustainability criteria.
These three projects could become the pillars of a Sustainability Pact at the heart of the EU's new political cycle.
For we are in an acute ecological debt situation, and it would be more than justified that the Stability and Growth Pact, which applies to the public finances of the member states, finds an equivalent for objectives of a green Europe!
To achieve its goals, this Sustainability Pact will require coordinated action across all areas: climate, trade, taxation, agriculture, and innovation.
The EU should not hesitate to use its regulatory powers, for example: expanding the scope of legislation on eco-design and the "extended producer responsibility" for products placed on the market could significantly stimulate environmental innovation.
Massive investments will also be necessary.
The European Commission estimates that the EU will need an additional 180 billion euros in investments each year to meet its commitments under the Paris Agreement.
It is an achievable goal.
The European Investment Bank is already the largest multilateral actor providing climate-focused funding.
And the new EU budget and its investment plan, making the best use of private sector investments, could further strengthen the Union's capacity for action.
The financial sector will have to play a fundamental role: by disclosing financial information related to climate change, we can encourage the world's largest financial institutions, such as the Norwegian sovereign fund and BlackRock, to adopt a long-term vision and avoid what the Governor of the Bank of England, Mark Carney, referred to as the "tragedy of the horizon."
Finally, although some member states may see this as a risky project, we must engage in a debate on taxation, as well as on subsidies applicable to fossil fuels. In short, on the integration of sustainability into public spending.
Behind these projects and initiatives, the key lies in the methodology. For this "Green New Deal" to bear fruit, we must set ambitious goals and "missions" with both short- and long-term perspectives that have real societal resonance.
With the Member States and the European Parliament, we will have to determine a common roadmap and carry out in-depth discussions, just as we will with our regions, cities, businesses, trade unions and civil society.
All of this cannot be done overnight.
But we can no longer close our eyes and hold our breath to escape from the reality of our environment.
It's already very late to launch a European "Green New Deal." But it's not too late.
Let's not miss this new opportunity!
